    neo:source "../../../Data/ISBN_978-0-9835844-5-2_-_Collecting_Gold_Dust/result_data/2019_-_Sayadaw-U-Tejaniya-Collecting-Gold-Dust-Web-Book-1_-_local_converter.md"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text """The goal of Satipaṭṭhāna practice is to understand deeply. When there is right understanding, when we have true realization into the nature of things, there will be calm in the mind. This calm state is a by-product of understanding or insight. The real goal of this meditation is to understand.

How can we understand the nature of pain if we just stared at it and it disappeared? Please be patient. When there is pain, watch the resistance in the mind and do this only for as long as it is bearable. When you change your posture, be aware of two possible motivations behind it: 1) greed to be more comfortable, or 2) understanding that if you continue to sit in that position, your aversion will grow. You don’t want to be growing aversion any more than you want to be growing greed. Understanding that the pain might become too much, you let go of the pain and make yourself more comfortable to prevent the growth of aversion.

Finally, let’s discuss talking. We should try to practice right speech and only say what is necessary and wholesome and for this we do need mindfulness. Speaking is all around us in daily life. You do not want to cut off speech without awareness of what you need to do. Use some restraint and know, consider and understand before you speak. Then you will also know if there is a need to talk. If you wanted to say something and you refrained from speaking then continue to know and recognize that you are not speaking but see the thinking going on in the mind.

There are many things that can happen while you are talking. If you are triggered when you are talking to someone, the fact that you are triggered but are still there, with the person, might trigger other emotions like embarrassment or agitation. While the mind may still be agitated, at the very least, you can still be aware. The purpose of mindfulness of speech is not to have a perfectly wise response, but to have a mindful conversation. You may have lost your balance in that time but what you need to know is that mindfulness is present through it all. If you are strongly attached to ideas, there will be triggers when someone else presents a conflicting idea. It’s like North and South Korea being at war, separated by ideology. You can learn some lessons from these conversations when there is mindfulness. Whenever we say something wrong, we will suffer a little bit but if mindfulness stays with us, we will always learn.

If you are strongly attached to ideas, there will be triggers when someone else presents a conflicting idea.

Be a little extra careful at home. It is so much more interesting at home when mindfulness is always present, and especially when we bring mindfulness to daily life situations. In your talking to others you learn to see others’ intentions and learn to speak in a way that helps you to manage yourself and manage the conversation as well. We begin to know what we are going to say before we say it and eventually have time to choose the skillful path.

Dedication

This wonderful gift of Dhamma comes to you from the community of meditators and supporters for whom the Dhamma

has touched in unfathomable ways.

May you also reap the benefits of three levels of wisdom

through this Dhamma dana—

in understanding the profound Dhamma,

in practicing rightly the Dhamma and

in reaping the fruit of Dhamma.

And may Nibbāna be the absolute finale.

Sādhu! Sādhu! Sādhu!"""^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_328 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_110,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_144,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_19,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_269,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_313,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_314 ;
    neo:id "f7ee03d4b63d210298a83cc6a97579c8"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "Source document: COLLECTING GOLD DUST: Nurturing the Dhamma in Daily Living, Chapter: A Note from the Teacher, paragraph number 3, sentence number 2 on page 6"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text "So long as we are practicing, we are using the qualities of awareness (remembering what is wholesome), perseverance, wisdom, faith, and stability of mind."^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_329 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_274,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_330,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_87 ;
    neo:id "7073e9dafb2cc28f7129d87e65e5cc60"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "Source document: COLLECTING GOLD DUST: Nurturing the Dhamma in Daily Living, Chapter: A Note from the Teacher, paragraph number 3, sentence number 3 on page 6"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text "Over many years of retreats with my teacher, the late Shwe Oo Min Sayadaw (“Sayadawgyi”), I developed these powers, yet I did not use them in life and did not practice them except on retreat."^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_33 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_34,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_35,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_36,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_37 ;
    neo:id "96fe9e1dfa6fadc2fe9022d635ad6763"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "Source document: COLLECTING GOLD DUST: Nurturing the Dhamma in Daily Living, Chapter: Acknowledgements, paragraph number 1, sentence number 1 on page vii"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text "My special gratitude goes to my teacher, the late Venerable Shwe Oo Min Sayadaw Bhaddanta Kosalla Mahāthera, who taught me the Dhamma and right attitude for my spiritual development and meditation practice."^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_331 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_332,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_35,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_39 ;
    neo:id "c03b8aa7d504dc696111fe1f86e50813"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "Source document: COLLECTING GOLD DUST: Nurturing the Dhamma in Daily Living, Chapter: A Note from the Teacher, paragraph number 3, sentence number 4 on page 6"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text "I had to truly dedicate myself to them before I understood what “Dhammaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāmi: I go to the Dhamma for refuge” truly meant and what a true refuge the Dhamma truly is."^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_333 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_26,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_39 ;
    neo:id "0d84983ef7d974638b1753a42d036cb9"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "Source document: COLLECTING GOLD DUST: Nurturing the Dhamma in Daily Living, Chapter: A Note from the Teacher, paragraph number 4, sentence number 1 on page 6"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text "I was about 13 years old when I started to meditate."^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_334 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_323,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_335,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_336,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_337,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_338 ;
    neo:id "e4358bcd53795a75c87c7b23a4c42e51"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "Source document: COLLECTING GOLD DUST: Nurturing the Dhamma in Daily Living, Chapter: A Note from the Teacher, paragraph number 4, sentence number 2 on page 6"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text "I worked with a technique that required energetic, rhythmic breathing and got hooked on the pleasant physical sensation and calm that the experience brought."^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_339 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_340,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_39 ;
    neo:id "ee2d03c742498b39d8c7574cf61fe737"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "Source document: COLLECTING GOLD DUST: Nurturing the Dhamma in Daily Living, Chapter: A Note from the Teacher, paragraph number 4, sentence number 3 on page 6"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text "When I told Sayadawgyi about this and that I liked it, he was curious and asked me about my experiences."^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_341 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_148,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_342,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_343,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_344,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_65 ;
    neo:id "0376d5c3d43de8f8df4d0657c0c8ad27"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "Source document: COLLECTING GOLD DUST: Nurturing the Dhamma in Daily Living, Chapter: A Note from the Teacher, paragraph number 4, sentence number 4 on page 6"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text "He would tell me stories of other people’s special meditation experiences and this would make me want such experiences and motivated me to meditate very diligently."^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_345 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_161,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_39 ;
    neo:id "dbe298ce7a28170bd63c2325a8026573"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "Source document: COLLECTING GOLD DUST: Nurturing the Dhamma in Daily Living, Chapter: A Note from the Teacher, paragraph number 5, sentence number 2 on page 7"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text "I quickly caught on that when I maintained detailed mindfulness throughout the day, the feelings of calm and pleasantness could be sustained so I was zealous in maintaining mindfulness."^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_347 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_344,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_348,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_65 ;
    neo:id "e9a88f7127bfcfc2b602cd6a2f2df2a3"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "Source document: COLLECTING GOLD DUST: Nurturing the Dhamma in Daily Living, Chapter: A Note from the Teacher, paragraph number 5, sentence number 3 on page 7"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text "He also told me something that really stuck with me: be happy when I noticed anything about myself because it meant that I was aware of myself, that I was mindful."^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_349 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_161,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_39 ;
    neo:id "b216eaac099a79d0b7fdb3b728e9deef"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "Source document: COLLECTING GOLD DUST: Nurturing the Dhamma in Daily Living, Chapter: A Note from the Teacher, paragraph number 5, sentence number 4 on page 7"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text "I was so focused on the mindfulness that anything I noticed about myself became a source of joy: it meant I was mindful!"^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_350 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_351,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_352,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_39 ;
    neo:id "996302366431b6a4ebc2ea62a8f00918"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "Source document: COLLECTING GOLD DUST: Nurturing the Dhamma in Daily Living, Chapter: A Note from the Teacher, paragraph number 5, sentence number 5 on page 7"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text "It never mattered to me even if I discovered an undesirable quality because the point I saw was that I was mindful."^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_353 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_340,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_344 ;
    neo:id "e07f1cc8eef1e48a575294d54c48e20f"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "Source document: COLLECTING GOLD DUST: Nurturing the Dhamma in Daily Living, Chapter: A Note from the Teacher, paragraph number 5, sentence number 1 on page 7"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text "Sayadawgyi often asked me why certain things happened when I went to him to describe my experiences."^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_354 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_355,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_356,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_39,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_65 ;
    neo:id "e697ab740ccde80ffbf36382cb733115"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "Source document: COLLECTING GOLD DUST: Nurturing the Dhamma in Daily Living, Chapter: A Note from the Teacher, paragraph number 5, sentence number 2 on page 7"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text "One episode in particular was when he asked me to find out why the abdomen rises and falls (that was my main object at that time) and I said it was because of the breath."^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_357 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_336,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_65 ;
    neo:id "9400d144c392357c19d08eb6357ea28b"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "Source document: COLLECTING GOLD DUST: Nurturing the Dhamma in Daily Living, Chapter: A Note from the Teacher, paragraph number 5, sentence number 3 on page 7"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text "Then he asked why there was breathing."^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_358 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_359,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_39,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_83 ;
    neo:id "11a0c5f42ba4d03203ac026019618905"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "Source document: COLLECTING GOLD DUST: Nurturing the Dhamma in Daily Living, Chapter: A Note from the Teacher, paragraph number 5, sentence number 4 on page 7"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text "I did not know this answer, which prompted a six-day search to find out."^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_360 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_117,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_356,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_361,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_362,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_363,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_364,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_365,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_366,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_367 ;
    neo:id "e828b49c88c5ca42f0b9cf0780410b8a"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "Source document: COLLECTING GOLD DUST: Nurturing the Dhamma in Daily Living, Chapter: A Note from the Teacher, paragraph number 5, sentence number 5 on page 7"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text "Every day, at every sit, the question dogged my observation of the breath and I remember on day six when the curious mind thought about why it was breathing and I saw the desire to breathe."^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_368 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_330,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_369,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_370,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_371,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_83 ;
    neo:id "62c765c4fb36b1ea3af41f30fbf0bc04"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "Source document: COLLECTING GOLD DUST: Nurturing the Dhamma in Daily Living, Chapter: A Note from the Teacher, paragraph number 5, sentence number 6 on page 7"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text "This episode and the success I had in finding the answer was so thrilling that I ran out of the dhamma hall immediately to tell my teacher the answer."^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_372 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_344,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_373 ;
    neo:id "34cc8a3b841c04d37fdcd38c3cf10197"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "Source document: COLLECTING GOLD DUST: Nurturing the Dhamma in Daily Living, Chapter: A Note from the Teacher, paragraph number 6, sentence number 2 on page 9"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text "It has fueled an eternal curiosity in me to observe and investigate, which of course has led to all sorts of discoveries."^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_375 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_376,
        ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_377 ;
    neo:id "e4c546da6a349233572cd457ea580d3d"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "Source document: COLLECTING GOLD DUST: Nurturing the Dhamma in Daily Living, Chapter: A Note from the Teacher, paragraph number 6, sentence number 1 on page 9"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text "Many types of insights can be awakened."^^xsd:string .

ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_379 a neo:Document ;
    neo:MENTIONS ex:node_4_cbedb183_7ddf_4a42_a9be_ef770b56f14a_19,
